There's a man sitting on a chair, biting a lip. He's not much older than you. When you open the door, he looks up. His hair is maintained, swooping upward, showing a bit of personality even if it matches the letter of the regulations. You've learned how to keep your own hair in check over the years, but for you that's about brute force, about forcing it into submission. For him, it's a work of art.

"I'm here to help," you say.

He snorts. "Forgive me if I think that's highly unlikely. You don't exactly look like a doctor."

