::Part 3[bookmark]

Another day, another job. As a Courier, you work for clients on both sides of the border, even if it isn't strictly legal in Over. It's not so weird to find yourself ringing the doorbell of one house, no different than any other house. Last job of the evening. An extraction, Wes said. Client was anonymous, wanted to meet at this location. DESCRIPTION OF HOUSE.

When the door opens, Kurt Hummel is standing there. You blink a few times. It's been three weeks since you extracted him across the border, and you weren't sure you'd ever see him again. He smiles when he sees you, warm and delighted, showing off the slightest hint of teeth. "Hello," he says. "Come on in."

"Hi," you say as you step inside. "How's your father doing?" Inside, the house is immaculate, neat, much like the one you grew up in yourself, but it feels subtly different somehow. There are photographs with bright easy smiles and the wood of the bannister looks worn in and smooth.

The smile on Kurt's face softens. "Better," he says. "It looks like he'll make a full recovery. He's even told me to stop hovering, because I was apparently--" He bites his lip. "Thanks for asking." There's a sweetness there, and you wonder how close he is to his father. You could go back to visit your parents, but you're not sure if they'd want-- if you could go back home and see them. You remember how they were when Cooper left, quiet and stoic and carrying on.

"I'm glad," you say. "I hope he makes a full recovery. You didn't get in trouble for--"

"No," he says. "They can't make any accusations about me or my father until he's better, and the hospital, and they don't have any real evidence about what we've been working on, just rumors."

"That's good," you say.

He watches you, steady and focused. "I wasn't sure it'd be-- that you'd be the one to show up today. I wanted to thank you for..." He trails off, and his face flushes pink.

You don't know what to say to that, so the two of you stand there for a few seconds, trying to pick up a conversational thread. "So," you finally manage to get out, clearing your throat. "Wes mentioned that you wanted an extraction? Who's the lucky person?"

"Me," Kurt says.

That wasn't what you were expecting, especially with how stressful his last extraction was.  "Oh," you say. "Sure, we can do that." He probably just needs to talk to Mr. Shue again about whatever mysterious project they're putting together face-to-face. There's only so much you can do when it takes a few days to get a message across the border.

"Could I... what's it like over there? Could you show it to me?" he asks. He says it like he's expecting you to say no.

Maybe you should say no. You don't really have time to babysit someone new around Under, where saying the wrong thing to the wrong person is the fastest way to get killed. There are always new jobs

But you do remember what it was like, the first time you ventured over the border, how big and intense and scary it all was. Kurt is-- Kurt reminds you of yourself, lonely and trying to find somewhere, anywhere you could possibly fit. You could make things easier for him than it ever was for you.

"Sure," you say.

